cket. The pattern of cricket as a sport and as a tourist attraction is highly dynamic. This volume examines how cricket as a participant and spectator sport generates diverse tourism to both major and peripheral locations. It looks at the ways in which cricket's extended duration (compared to other sports) creates a different dynamic in terms of visitor-host interaction. It also considers how following cricket as a tourist and a participant causes exposure to unique pressures and results in unique behaviour. The book will appeal to researchers, students and teachers in tourism, sport and leisure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCricket. 0aSports and tourism. 4aSPORTS & OUTDOOR RECREATION. 4aTourism industry. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  acricket.  afan identity.  aspectator participation.  asport tourism.  asport.  atourism.  atourist behaviour.1 aAli, Nazia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaum, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaum, Tom, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBeech, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCardwell, Denise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmery, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrost, Warwick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKerr, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaitland, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoakes, Steve, econ